WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.580
 - Hello and welcome through another walkthrough for computer architecture for everybody.

00:00:05.580 --> 00:00:08.780
 In this walkthrough, I am going to walk through the building

00:00:08.780 --> 00:00:10.840
 of a slightly more complex circuit.

00:00:10.840 --> 00:00:14.040
 In this case, we are going to build a NAND gate.

00:00:14.040 --> 00:00:17.020
 So NAND of course is the opposite of AND.

00:00:17.020 --> 00:00:20.160
 So if both inputs are one, the output is zero.

00:00:20.160 --> 00:00:22.760
 And if any of the outputs are zero, the output is one.

00:00:22.760 --> 00:00:24.180
 It's the opposite of AND.

00:00:24.180 --> 00:00:26.240
 And so let's take a look at the picture.

00:00:26.240 --> 00:00:29.000
 So the way this works is there are two inputs

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:32.180
 and there is a set of PMOS transistors at the top,

00:00:32.180 --> 00:00:34.780
 kind of in parallel going from the positive voltage

00:00:34.780 --> 00:00:37.120
 to a common wire in the middle to out.

00:00:37.120 --> 00:00:40.460
 And then there is a set of NMOS transistors in series

00:00:40.460 --> 00:00:41.920
 between the out and the ground.

00:00:41.920 --> 00:00:43.800
 'Cause this is CMOS circuitry.

00:00:43.800 --> 00:00:47.380
 The goal is to either have VDD come out or ground to come out,

00:00:47.380 --> 00:00:49.520
 depending on A and B in the combination,

00:00:49.520 --> 00:00:50.580
 based on the truth table.

00:00:50.580 --> 00:00:52.300
 So let's go ahead and draw this.

00:00:52.300 --> 00:00:54.820
 So I'm gonna draw this in a little more traditional way

00:00:54.820 --> 00:00:56.820
 than I did in my previous demonstration.

00:00:56.820 --> 00:01:00.340
 It's pretty common to just draw a line across the top

00:01:00.340 --> 00:01:02.860
 and put the VCC across the top.

00:01:02.860 --> 00:01:04.980
 So you see that we're sort of emulating

00:01:04.980 --> 00:01:07.140
 a lot of what these diagrams look like.

00:01:07.140 --> 00:01:09.460
 And then what I wanna do is I wanna create

00:01:09.460 --> 00:01:12.820
 two P transistors, so the A and the B.

00:01:12.820 --> 00:01:16.220
 And so I'm gonna drop a little bit of P-dope silicon down.

00:01:16.220 --> 00:01:18.300
 I'm gonna give myself plenty of space

00:01:18.300 --> 00:01:22.140
 and make these plenty long, okay?

00:01:22.140 --> 00:01:24.460
 And then I'm gonna make some transistors there

00:01:24.460 --> 00:01:26.380
 by putting some poly across.

00:01:26.380 --> 00:01:27.340
 I'm gonna put it like,

00:01:27.340 --> 00:01:29.620
 I'm gonna keep this really tiny for now, okay?

00:01:29.620 --> 00:01:30.700
 So there's some poly.

00:01:30.700 --> 00:01:31.860
 So there's two transistors.

00:01:31.860 --> 00:01:34.920
 So we just made, by crossing the P-dope silicon

00:01:34.920 --> 00:01:36.580
 and the poly silicon twice,

00:01:36.580 --> 00:01:40.340
 we now have transistors that we can hook A and B up to.

00:01:40.340 --> 00:01:41.820
 We'll wire them up later.

00:01:41.820 --> 00:01:44.220
 And then what we're gonna do is we're gonna make the output.

00:01:44.220 --> 00:01:46.980
 I'll just make the output be a horizontal piece

00:01:46.980 --> 00:01:47.880
 of metal wire.

00:01:47.880 --> 00:01:50.020
 Now I've gotta put some vias in here

00:01:50.020 --> 00:01:52.860
 so I can connect the P-dope silicon to the metal

00:01:52.860 --> 00:01:53.700
 where I need to.

00:01:53.700 --> 00:01:55.500
 So let's punch a couple of vias in.

00:01:55.500 --> 00:01:57.620
 Via, via, via, via.

00:01:57.620 --> 00:02:00.780
 So now the orange P-dope silicon

00:02:00.780 --> 00:02:02.540
 and the metals are connected.

00:02:02.540 --> 00:02:05.020
 Okay, so the next thing we need to do

00:02:05.020 --> 00:02:08.980
 is we need to make some NMOS transistors down at the bottom.

00:02:08.980 --> 00:02:11.020
 So let's grab some N-dope silicon

00:02:11.020 --> 00:02:14.340
 and hook this up here.

00:02:14.340 --> 00:02:20.320
 And then, oops, I need to fix that.

00:02:20.320 --> 00:02:21.500
 I need to erase that.

00:02:21.500 --> 00:02:24.820
 I need to give myself a little space here.

00:02:26.020 --> 00:02:27.900
 So I wanna make some N-dope silicon

00:02:27.900 --> 00:02:30.360
 that kinda comes down from the center wire a little bit.

00:02:30.360 --> 00:02:34.300
 And then I am going to make some more N-dope silicon.

00:02:34.300 --> 00:02:36.380
 Actually, I don't know if I need to do that.

00:02:36.380 --> 00:02:39.800
 Let's try to make it in one big piece of N-dope silicon.

00:02:39.800 --> 00:02:41.660
 Let me make my N-dope silicon longer.

00:02:41.660 --> 00:02:44.360
 And now let's put some polysilicon in

00:02:44.360 --> 00:02:46.180
 to make two more transistors.

00:02:46.180 --> 00:02:49.120
 So we're gonna put transistor here

00:02:49.120 --> 00:02:51.000
 and then another transistor here.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:52.420
 So that's two transistors,

00:02:52.420 --> 00:02:55.280
 two NMOS transistors that are right there.

00:02:55.280 --> 00:02:58.820
 And I think I might as well put my ground in now,

00:02:58.820 --> 00:03:00.340
 the ground down here.

00:03:00.340 --> 00:03:03.900
 Traditionally, you sorta draw that as a long horizontal line.

00:03:03.900 --> 00:03:07.040
 I will place some zero or ground voltage

00:03:07.040 --> 00:03:08.860
 and then I'll place a couple of vias

00:03:08.860 --> 00:03:12.140
 to make sure to connect the green N-dope silicon

00:03:12.140 --> 00:03:14.380
 to the metal in both of the places.

00:03:14.380 --> 00:03:16.640
 So I think we mostly have this,

00:03:16.640 --> 00:03:19.420
 except now we've gotta take our inputs

00:03:19.420 --> 00:03:21.500
 and connect them to those transistors.

00:03:21.500 --> 00:03:24.020
 So let's make an A input for now.

00:03:24.020 --> 00:03:25.340
 Let's make a little bit of metal.

00:03:25.340 --> 00:03:26.400
 This shouldn't be too hard.

00:03:26.400 --> 00:03:29.000
 So let's just say this is our A input

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:31.920
 and then we're gonna hook that to here.

00:03:31.920 --> 00:03:34.260
 I wanna make that a little longer.

00:03:34.260 --> 00:03:36.600
 So I'm gonna make my pink a little bit longer.

00:03:36.600 --> 00:03:38.140
 I'm gonna put A on this one,

00:03:38.140 --> 00:03:39.740
 which is a little bit different.

00:03:39.740 --> 00:03:41.580
 So here's the thing.

00:03:41.580 --> 00:03:44.020
 I can paint this pink, so now I have an overlap.

00:03:44.020 --> 00:03:45.200
 See how I painted that pink

00:03:45.200 --> 00:03:46.800
 so it overlaps with the metal now?

00:03:46.800 --> 00:03:50.580
 So I can pop a via in there, punch, punch.

00:03:50.580 --> 00:03:54.100
 So that is my A.

00:03:54.100 --> 00:03:55.900
 Let's go ahead and mark that with a probe.

00:03:55.900 --> 00:03:57.300
 Let's mark that as A.

00:03:57.300 --> 00:04:00.820
 Okay, and now we've gotta have B.

00:04:00.820 --> 00:04:03.660
 B is a little bit trickier.

00:04:03.660 --> 00:04:05.580
 Where am I gonna, well, let's start with B, E.

00:04:05.580 --> 00:04:07.020
 Let's put B in easy.

00:04:07.020 --> 00:04:10.420
 Let's make B, B here.

00:04:10.420 --> 00:04:14.220
 Okay, so then let's put the contact of B,

00:04:14.220 --> 00:04:17.660
 the probe B right there.

00:04:17.660 --> 00:04:18.940
 So now I have B.

00:04:18.940 --> 00:04:22.360
 Now the key thing is I've got to get this B

00:04:22.360 --> 00:04:26.500
 up to this second PMOS gate.

00:04:26.500 --> 00:04:28.700
 So I could do a lot of things here.

00:04:28.700 --> 00:04:31.220
 I could route it up here, and I'll route it over there.

00:04:31.220 --> 00:04:32.980
 Or I could route it over here,

00:04:32.980 --> 00:04:34.700
 and then route it down to here.

00:04:34.700 --> 00:04:36.380
 So I think I'm gonna come through here.

00:04:36.380 --> 00:04:37.640
 So you're gonna see something.

00:04:37.640 --> 00:04:39.140
 I'm gonna take this polysilicon.

00:04:39.140 --> 00:04:40.260
 And in a real circuit,

00:04:40.260 --> 00:04:43.280
 you might find that this is kinda, oh, look what I can do.

00:04:43.280 --> 00:04:44.900
 Because when I make this polysilicon

00:04:44.900 --> 00:04:46.900
 come across the metal right there,

00:04:46.900 --> 00:04:48.240
 it's not actually connected.

00:04:48.240 --> 00:04:50.100
 And then look, ooh, no, ooh, yikes.

00:04:50.100 --> 00:04:52.260
 I gotta erase it 'cause I made a kind of a blob.

00:04:52.260 --> 00:04:55.900
 I spilled some, I spilled some polysilicon.

00:04:55.900 --> 00:04:58.040
 So now I can actually connect this together.

00:04:58.040 --> 00:05:01.780
 Wow, I think that looks pretty easy at this point.

00:05:01.780 --> 00:05:02.620
 Did it work?

00:05:02.620 --> 00:05:07.500
 So I have my A connected to one of the PMOS transistors

00:05:07.500 --> 00:05:09.900
 and one of the NMOS transistors.

00:05:09.900 --> 00:05:11.220
 And then I have my B connected

00:05:11.220 --> 00:05:13.060
 to one of the NMOS transistors

00:05:13.060 --> 00:05:14.660
 and one of the PMOS transistors.

00:05:14.660 --> 00:05:17.580
 I have a feeling that it is right.

00:05:17.580 --> 00:05:20.180
 And I think if we look at our assignment,

00:05:20.180 --> 00:05:22.620
 we're supposed to make a Q as the output.

00:05:22.620 --> 00:05:25.920
 So let's put another probe here on the output, Q.

00:05:25.920 --> 00:05:28.620
 So I could run the autograder.

00:05:28.620 --> 00:05:29.500
 I think I got it.

00:05:29.500 --> 00:05:30.340
 I think I made one.

00:05:30.340 --> 00:05:31.160
 It's pretty good here.

00:05:31.160 --> 00:05:34.200
 But one of the things I do to test these things is,

00:05:34.200 --> 00:05:36.300
 oh, I didn't mean to put that via there.

00:05:36.300 --> 00:05:37.400
 Put a VCC there.

00:05:37.400 --> 00:05:40.600
 So now I can see that I put a plus in the A area

00:05:40.600 --> 00:05:43.780
 and it stops the PMOS, but it does transmit.

00:05:43.780 --> 00:05:45.500
 But then I have to put like,

00:05:45.500 --> 00:05:49.340
 let's put a VCC where the B is now.

00:05:49.340 --> 00:05:50.340
 Oh, I'm missing a via.

00:05:50.340 --> 00:05:52.860
 See how the voltage comes here in the one

00:05:52.860 --> 00:05:54.320
 and it hits this overlap?

00:05:54.320 --> 00:05:57.980
 I gotta put a via there because it doesn't really touch.

00:05:57.980 --> 00:05:58.820
 Boop.

00:05:58.820 --> 00:06:00.600
 So now I think we got it.

00:06:00.600 --> 00:06:05.600
 A is one and B is one and the output is zero,

00:06:05.600 --> 00:06:07.300
 which is good.

00:06:07.300 --> 00:06:08.300
 So we can keep testing it.

00:06:08.300 --> 00:06:10.760
 I just tested by popping a ground in here.

00:06:10.760 --> 00:06:14.220
 So now we have A is zero and B is one

00:06:14.220 --> 00:06:17.180
 and the output is one, which is what it's supposed to be

00:06:17.180 --> 00:06:18.260
 'cause it's a NAND gate.

00:06:18.260 --> 00:06:21.260
 So I'm gonna go back to putting the probes in.

00:06:21.260 --> 00:06:24.500
 So you notice how I can just kind of overwrite this stuff.

00:06:24.500 --> 00:06:28.020
 So there's A and I got the probe B now.

00:06:28.020 --> 00:06:29.540
 Now I can actually start the grader.

00:06:29.540 --> 00:06:31.700
 I think it'll go through all the combinations

00:06:31.700 --> 00:06:34.380
 in the truth table and it will tell us

00:06:34.380 --> 00:06:36.320
 if it likes the circuit that we built.

00:06:36.320 --> 00:06:37.840
 So let's go ahead.

00:06:37.840 --> 00:06:40.060
 Check for the A, B and Q probes.

00:06:40.060 --> 00:06:41.420
 They seem to be there.

00:06:41.420 --> 00:06:43.820
 Test, let's set A to zero and B to zero

00:06:43.820 --> 00:06:45.700
 and is the output one?

00:06:45.700 --> 00:06:48.420
 A is zero, B is zero, output's one, yes it is.

00:06:48.420 --> 00:06:52.660
 Set A to zero and B to one, is the output zero?

00:06:52.660 --> 00:06:55.060
 Oh no, the output's supposed to be one in that case, yep.

00:06:55.060 --> 00:06:59.020
 So this is a, and then if we do A to one and B to zero,

00:06:59.020 --> 00:07:03.020
 the output is one and then if we set them both to one,

00:07:03.020 --> 00:07:05.260
 the output is zero, which it's a NAND gate.

00:07:05.260 --> 00:07:08.200
 And so we finished and away we go.

00:07:08.200 --> 00:07:12.020
 So there we did, we took and viewed this image

00:07:12.020 --> 00:07:14.700
 and made ourselves the gate by laying it out.

00:07:14.700 --> 00:07:17.220
 And again, I tend to start by laying transistors out

00:07:17.220 --> 00:07:19.500
 but you gotta give yourself a little space

00:07:19.500 --> 00:07:22.260
 as you lay these things out and put them together.

00:07:22.260 --> 00:07:23.940
 Now I've built them a few times.

00:07:23.940 --> 00:07:25.380
 The first few that you're gonna build

00:07:25.380 --> 00:07:26.640
 are going to be a little tricky

00:07:26.640 --> 00:07:29.460
 but it's very satisfying when you get them finished.

00:07:29.460 --> 00:07:32.140
 So I hope you enjoyed this walkthrough

00:07:32.140 --> 00:07:34.700
 for computer architecture on the building of a gate

00:07:34.700 --> 00:07:36.240
 using a VLSI design tool.

00:07:36.240 --> 00:07:38.820
 (upbeat music)

